    <subsection>
        <title>Measuring Pyramids</title>
        <p>
            We shall compute measurements a specific example, the pyramid with height 4 and 
            3 by 4 rectangular base. Then we can attempt to generalize some of our observations 
            to other pyramids and cylinders.
        </p>
        <exploration xml:id="explor-rect-pyr">
            <title>Exploring a Rectangular Pyramid</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Throughout this activity, we will explore the rectangular pyramid 
                    that is created by folding the net in 
                    <xref ref="fig-explor-rect-pyr"/>. 
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-explor-rect-pyr">
                    <caption>
                        Rectangular Pyramid for <xref ref="explor-rect-pyr"/>
                    </caption>
                    <image source="PyramidNet434.png">
                        <shortdescription>
                            A net that can be folded to create a 
                            rectangular pyramid.
                        </shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </introduction>
            <task xml:id="construct-rect-pyr">
                <title>Constructing a pyramid from a net</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Print a copy of this net, cut it out, and fold along the 
                        dashed lines to see that this forms a rectangular pyramid.
                        Stiffer paper such as cardstock is recommended.
                        What do you notice about the corner at <m>C</m>?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <hint>
                    <p>
                        You will use this construction again near the end of this exploration. 
                        Keep it in good condition!
                    </p>
                </hint>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="lengths-rect-pyr">
                <title>Finding Edge Lengths and Surface Area</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Here <m>ABCD</m> is a rectangle with <m>AD=4</m> and <m>CD=3</m>. 
                        Angles <m>\angle DCG</m>, <m>\angle ADH</m>, <m>\angle ABE</m>,
                        and <m>\angle BCF</m> are right angles and <m>CG=4</m>. Determine 
                        the following:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Determine <m>GD</m>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Determine <m>BF</m>.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Explain why <m>DH=GD</m> and <m>EB=BF</m>.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Determine <m>AE</m>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Use your knowledge of rectangles and triangles and 
                                the definition of surface area to 
                                determine the surface area of this rectangular pyramid.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exploration>
        <p>
            With both prisms and pyramids, formulas exist to compute the surface area of some of 
            the common types, but these formulas are not necessary. If we can compute the areas of 
            each face, then the surface area is simply the sum of the areas of the faces. 
        </p>
        <p>
            How can we find the volume of a pyramid? It is a fact that the volume of a pyramid is
            exactly one-third of the volume of the prism with the same stretch distance. Since we know that 
            the volume of a prism is <m>V=Ad</m>, the volume of a pyramid must be 
            <m>V=\frac{Ad}{3}</m> where <m>A</m> is the area of the base and <m>d</m> is the 
            stretch distance or height. In fact, this works for cones as well. The volume of a 
            cone is <m>V=\frac{(\pi r^2)d}{3}</m> since the area of the circular base is 
            <m>A=\pi r^2</m>.
        </p>
    </subsection>
