            <exercise xml:id="EC-why-third">
                <title>Visualizing the Volume Formula for a Rectangular Pyramid</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Print the three nets in <xref ref="nets-three"/> on stiff 
                        paper. The scale factor of any enlargements should be consistent.
                        Cut out the nets and fold each to create a rectangular pyramid, taping 
                        the edges as needed.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="nets-three">
                        <caption>Nets for <xref ref="EC-why-third"/></caption>
                        <image source="threePyramidNet434.png">
                            <shortdescription>Nets for three rectangular pyramids; two have a 
                                3 by 4-rectangular base and height 4. The other has a 
                                4 by 4-square base and height 3.
                            </shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <p> 
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Use the formula <m>V=\frac{Ad}{3}</m> to determine the volume 
                                of each pyramid. Note that two pyramids should be identical.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Put the three pyramids together so that they form a 
                                    <m>3\times 4\times 4</m>-rectangular prism. How does this 
                                    demonstrate that the formula <m>V=\frac{Ad}{3}</m> holds for 
                                    this particular pyramid?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
